{"text": "2.3  Measurement of Length
You are already familiar with some direct methods for the measurement of length.", "fibs": ["Length"]}
{"text": "For example, a metre scale is used for lengths from 10–3 m to 102 m.  A vernier callipers is used for lengths to an accuracy of 10–4 m.  A screw gauge and a spherometer can be used to measure lengths as less as to 10–5 m. To measure lengths beyond these ranges, we make use of some special indirect methods.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "2.3.1  Measurement of Large Distances
Large distances such as the distance of a planet or a star from the earth cannot be measured directly with a metre scale.", "fibs": ["distance"]}
{"text": "An important method in such cases is the parallax method.", "fibs": ["method"]}
{"text": "When you hold a pencil in front of you against some specific point on the background (a wall) and look at the pencil first through your left eye A (closing the right eye) and then look at the pencil through your right eye B (closing the left eye), you would notice that the position of the pencil seems to change with respect to the point on the wall.", "fibs": ["pencil"]}
{"text": "This is called parallax.", "fibs": ["parallax"]}
{"text": "The distance between the two points of observation is called the basis.", "fibs": ["distance"]}
{"text": "In this example, the basis is the distance between the eyes.", "fibs": ["example"]}
