2.3.2 Estimation of Very Small Distances: Size of a Molecule
To measure a very small size, like that of a molecule (10–8 m to 10–10 m), we have to adopt special methods.", "fibs": ["Answer"]}
{"text": "We cannot use a screw gauge or similar instruments.", "fibs": ["use"]}
{"text": "Even a microscope has certain limitations.", "fibs": ["microscope"]}
{"text": "An optical microscope uses visible light to ‘look’ at the system under investigation.", "fibs": ["microscope"]}
{"text": "As light has wave like features, the resolution to which an optical microscope can be used is the wavelength of light (A detailed explanation can be found in the Class XII Physics textbook).", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "For visible light the range of wavelengths  is from about 4000 Å to 7000 Å  (1 angstrom = 1 Å = 10-10 m).", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "Hence an optical microscope cannot resolve particles with sizes smaller than this.", "fibs": ["microscope"]}
{"text": "Instead of visible light, we can use an electron beam.", "fibs": ["light"]}
{"text": "The resolution of such an electron microscope is limited finally by the fact that electrons can also behave as waves !", "fibs": ["resolution"]}
{"text": "(You will learn more about this in class XII).", "fibs": ["class"]}
{"text": "The wavelength of an electron can be as small as a fraction of an angstrom.", "fibs": ["wavelength"]}
{"text": "Such electron microscopes with a resolution of 0.6 Å have been built.", "fibs": ["electron"]}
{"text": "They can almost resolve atoms and molecules in a material.", "fibs": ["material"]}
{"text": "In recent times, tunnelling microscopy has been developed in which again the limit of resolution is better than an angstrom.", "fibs": ["microscopy"]}
{"text": "It is possible to estimate the sizes of molecules.", "fibs": ["estimate"]}
{"text": "A simple method for estimating the molecular size of oleic acid is given below.", "fibs": ["method"]}
{"text": "Oleic acid is a soapy liquid with large molecular size of the order of 10–9 m.
