2.5   Measurement of time
To measure any time interval we need a clock.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "We now use an atomic standard of time, which is based on the periodic vibrations produced in a cesium atom.", "fibs": ["use"]}
{"text": "This is the basis of the cesium clock, sometimes called atomic clock, used in the national standards.", "fibs": ["basis"]}
{"text": "In the cesium atomic clock, the second is taken as the time needed for 9,192,631,770 vibrations of the radiation corresponding to the transition between the two hyperfine levels of the ground state of cesium-133 atom.", "fibs": ["cesium"]}
{"text": "The vibrations of the cesium atom regulate the rate of this cesium atomic clock just as the vibrations of a balance wheel regulate an ordinary wristwatch or the vibrations of a small quartz crystal regulate a quartz wristwatch.", "fibs": ["cesium"]}
{"text": "The cesium atomic clocks are very accurate.", "fibs": ["cesium"]}
{"text": "In principle they provide portable standard.", "fibs": ["principle"]}
{"text": "The national standard of time interval ‘second’ as well as the frequency is maintained through four cesium atomic clocks.", "fibs": ["time"]}
{"text": "A cesium atomic clock is used at the National Physical Laboratory (NPL), New Delhi to  maintain the Indian standard of time.", "fibs": ["cesium"]}
{"text": "In our country, the NPL has the responsibility of maintenance and improvement of physical standards, including that of time, frequency, etc.", "fibs": ["country"]}
{"text": "Note that the Indian Standard Time (IST) is linked to this set of atomic clocks.", "fibs": ["IST"]}
{"text": "The efficient cesium atomic clocks are so accurate that they impart the uncertainty in time realisation as ± 1 × 10–13, i.e.", "fibs": ["cesium"]}
{"text": "1 part in 1013.", "fibs": ["part"]}
{"text": "This implies that the uncertainty gained over time by such a device is less than 1 part in 1013; they lose or gain no more than 3 µs in one year.", "fibs": ["uncertainty"]}
{"text": "In view of the tremendous accuracy in time measurement, the SI unit of length has been expressed in terms the path length light travels in certain interval of time (1/299, 792, 458 of a second) (Table 2.1).", "fibs": ["view"]}
{"text": "The time interval of events that we come across in the universe vary over a very wide range.", "fibs": ["time"]}
{"text": "Table 2.5 gives the range and order of some typical time intervals.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "You may notice that there is an interesting coincidence between the numbers appearing in Tables 2.3 and 2.5.", "fibs": ["notice"]}
{"text": "Note that the ratio of the longest and shortest lengths of objects in our universe is about 1041.", "fibs": ["ratio"]}
{"text": "Interestingly enough, the ratio of the longest and shortest time intervals associated with the events and objects in our universe is also about 1041.", "fibs": ["ratio"]}
{"text": "This number, 1041 comes up again in Table 2.4, which lists typical masses of objects.", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "The ratio of the largest and smallest masses of the objects in our universe is about (1041)2.", "fibs": ["ratio"]}
{"text": "Is this a curious coincidence between these large numbers purely accidental ?", "fibs": ["coincidence"]}
{"text": "2.6	Accuracy, precision of instruments and errors in measurement
Measurement is the foundation of all experimental science and technology.", "fibs": ["Accuracy"]}
{"text": "The result of every measurement by any measuring instrument contains some uncertainty.", "fibs": ["result"]}
{"text": "This uncertainty is called error.", "fibs": ["uncertainty"]}
{"text": "Every calculated quantity which is based on measured values, also has an error.", "fibs": ["quantity"]}
{"text": "We shall distinguish between two terms: accuracy and precision.", "fibs": ["accuracy"]}
{"text": "The accuracy of a measurement is a measure of how close the measured value is to the true value of the quantity.", "fibs": ["accuracy"]}
{"text": "Precision tells us to what resolution or limit the quantity is measured.", "fibs": ["resolution"]}
{"text": "The accuracy in measurement may depend on several factors, including the limit or the resolution of the measuring instrument.", "fibs": ["accuracy"]}
{"text": "For example, suppose the true value of a certain length is near 3.678 cm.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "In one experiment, using a measuring instrument of resolution 0.1 cm, the measured value is found to be 3.5 cm, while in another experiment using a measuring device of greater resolution, say 0.01 cm, the length is determined to be 3.38 cm.", "fibs": ["experiment"]}
{"text": "The first measurement has more accuracy (because it is closer to the true value) but less precision (its resolution is only 0.1 cm), while the second measurement is less accurate but more precise.", "fibs": ["measurement"]}
{"text": "Thus every measurement is approximate due to errors in measurement.", "fibs": ["measurement"]}
{"text": "In general, the errors in measurement can be broadly classified as (a) systematic errors and (b) random errors.", "fibs": ["measurement"]}
{"text": "Table 2.5   Range and order of time intervals






Systematic errors
The systematic errors are those errors that tend to be in one direction, either positive or negative.", "fibs": ["Table"]}
{"text": "Some of the sources of systematic errors are :
(a) 	Instrumental errors that arise from the errors due to imperfect design or calibration of the measuring instrument, zero error in the instrument, etc.", "fibs": ["design"]}
{"text": "For example, the temperature graduations of a thermometer may be inadequately calibrated (it may read 104 °C at the boiling point of water at STP whereas it should read 100 °C); in a vernier callipers the zero mark of vernier scale may not coincide with the zero mark of the main scale, or simply an ordinary metre scale may be worn off at one end.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "(b) 	Imperfection in experimental technique or procedure To determine the temperature of a human body, a thermometer placed under the armpit will always give a temperature lower than the actual value of the body temperature.", "fibs": ["b"]}
{"text": "Other external conditions (such as changes in temperature, humidity, wind velocity, etc.)", "fibs": ["temperature"]}
{"text": "during the experiment may systematically affect the measurement.", "fibs": ["experiment"]}
{"text": "(c) 	Personal errors that arise due to an individual’s bias, lack of proper setting of the apparatus or individual’s carelessness in taking observations without observing proper precautions, etc.", "fibs": ["’"]}
{"text": "For example, if you, by habit, always hold your head a bit too far to the right while reading the position of a needle on the scale, you will introduce an error due to parallax.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Systematic errors can be minimised by improving experimental techniques, selecting better instruments and removing personal bias as far as possible.", "fibs": ["bias"]}
{"text": "For a given set-up, these errors may be estimated to a certain extent and the necessary corrections may be applied to the readings.", "fibs": ["set-up"]}
{"text": "Random errors
The random errors are those errors, which occur irregularly and hence are random with respect to sign and size.", "fibs": ["respect"]}
{"text": "unpredictable fluctuations in temperature, voltage supply, mechanical vibrations of experimental set-ups, etc), personal (unbiased) errors by the observer taking readings, etc.", "fibs": ["temperature"]}
{"text": "For example, when the same person repeats the same observation, it is very likely that he may get different readings everytime.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Least count error
The smallest value that can be measured by the measuring instrument is called its least count.", "fibs": ["count"]}
{"text": "All the readings or measured values are good only up to this value.", "fibs": ["value"]}
{"text": "The least count error is the error associated with the resolution of the instrument.", "fibs": ["count"]}
{"text": "For example, a vernier callipers has the least count as 0.01cm; a spherometer may have a least count of 0.001 cm.", "fibs": ["example"]}
{"text": "Least count error belongs to the category of random errors but within a limited size; it occurs with both systematic and random errors.", "fibs": ["count"]}
{"text": "If we use a metre scale for measurement of length, it may have graduations at 1 mm division scale spacing or interval.", "fibs": ["use"]}
{"text": "Using instruments of higher precision, improving experimental techniques, etc., we can reduce the least count error.", "fibs": ["precision"]}
{"text": "Repeating the observations several times and taking the arithmetic mean of all the observations, the mean value would be very close to the true value of the measured quantity.", "fibs": ["arithmetic"]}
