{"text": "2.33	A great physicist of this century (P.A.M. Dirac) loved playing with numerical values of Fundamental constants of nature.", "fibs": ["physicist"]}
{"text": "This led him to an interesting observation.", "fibs": ["observation"]}
{"text": "Dirac found that from the basic constants of atomic physics (c, e, mass of electron, mass of proton) and the gravitational constant G, he could arrive at a number with the dimension of time.", "fibs": ["physics"]}
{"text": "Further, it was a very large number, its magnitude being close to the present estimate on the age of the universe (~15 billion years).", "fibs": ["number"]}
{"text": "From the table of fundamental constants in this book, try to see if you too can construct this number (or any other interesting number you can think of ).", "fibs": ["table"]}
